<p>Hello everyone, today We going to walk through Devvortex.</p>

<p>As ever, first of all, We have to add the provided IP in our <strong>/etc/hosts</strong> file as <strong>devvortex.htb.</strong></p>

<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," style="height:415px; width:1080px" /></p>

<p>The site it&#39;s pretty simple and represents a presentation page for devvortex.</p>

<p>Let&#39;s start with the fingerprinting phase to get some useful information (We Hope).</p>

<p>My first try was with <strong>gobuster </strong>in <strong>dir</strong> and <strong>vhost</strong> mode.</p>

<p>Unfortunately, We don&#39;t have any information about the programming language used to create the page so We can use a generic directory listing wordlist from <a href="https://github.com/danielmiessler/SecLists">SecList</a>.</p>

<p>The exploit finds two user and the login password for the user lewis, so let&#39;s loggin into the joomla dashboard.</p>

<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," /></p>

<p>Very well, lewis is the admin. So, considering that the site is written in PHP and lewis is an admin, We can simply create a new file uploading a PH reverse shell (I prefere the pentest-monkey <a href="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/pentestmonkey/php-reverse-shell/master/php-reverse-shell.php">one</a>)</p>

<p>If you don&#39;t know how to create a new page in joomla, this is pretty simple, you must go in Sistem &gt; Site Templates and after you choose the admin&#39;s site, you create a new file from the button.</p>

<p>To avoid other user to find my file I will name it using an UUID.</p>

<p>Remember, to get a reverse shell you must be connected to the HackTheBox VPN (OR JUST USE YOUR PUBLIC IP BUT CAN BE A BAD IDEA) and with a opened tcp listener (<strong>nc -nvlp [port]</strong>).</p>

<p>In the Pentest-Monkey reverse shell script you must insert your IP and Port for the connection, I prefere to use the preset port (1234) and provide my IP putting the <strong>$_GET[&quot;ip&quot;] </strong>command in the IP variable.</p>

<p>So let&#39;s open our listener with <strong>nc -nvlp 1234</strong> and then call our file providing a query parameter ip with our IP And.....</p>

<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," /></p>

<p>We got a shell.</p>

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; is specified, the bug report will contain more<br />
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; information.&nbsp; (Implied if pid is given as only<br />
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; argument.)<br />
&nbsp; --hanging&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The provided pid is a hanging application.<br />
&nbsp; -c PATH, --crash-file=PATH<br />
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Report the crash from given .apport or .crash file<br />
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; instead of the pending ones in /var/crash. (Implied if<br />
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; file is given as only argument.)<br />
&nbsp; --save=PATH&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In bug filing mode, save the collected information<br />
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; into a file instead of reporting it. This file can<br />
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; then be reported later on from a different machine.<br />
&nbsp; --tag=TAG&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Add an extra tag to the report. Can be specified<br />
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; multiple times.<br />
&nbsp; -v, --version&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Print the Apport version number.</p>
</div>

<p>Now We need to find a crash file to run the software and get the pager. If you take a look to the apport-cli documentation you can provide a PID. Now We have a solution:</p>

<ol>
	<li>run ps -aux to get a random PID</li>
	<li>run sudo /usr/bin/apport-cli [PID]</li>
	<li>Wait the software it&#39;s ready and then view the report using V</li>
	<li>When the pager it&#39;s ready write !/bin/bash</li>
</ol>
